[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wasn\'t great, so I didn\'t really do a full tutorial on version one. However, this new version 2 Pro that was just released is actually really good, as you can see from some of these demos. Now,'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here\'s how it works. It actually uses Alibaba\'s one 2.2, which is currently the best open-source video model. It\'s also the most uncensored, and it uses it to generate multiple clips of 4 to 5'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'seconds each, which is the optimum duration, and then it would glue all these clips together to create your final long video. The trick here is that each clip has to continue seamlessly from the previous clip. And SVI version'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'two is able to do this very well. Note that if you try to use one by itself, you could set the duration to longer like 20 or 30 seconds. But after like four to five seconds, the video starts'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to deteriorate quite significantly. Now, in the past, there are various tools that can use the last frame of one clip as the first frame of the next clip and so on and so forth. And then it can also stitch them together just like stable'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video infinity. However, in the past, you would often run into two main flaws. The first one is that the transition isn\'t very seamless. So, you can easily tell when one clip switches to the next clip. Another major issue is that the'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'longer the video, the more errors and noise and distortions you get, like by 20 or 30 seconds, the quality just starts to degrade considerably and the consistency just goes out the window.'

